toy3 <- read.csv("toy_example3.csv", header = TRUE)

Question 1 of 13

First fit a regression model using height and gender (Male) (i.e., Female is the reference group) as predictors for weight, assuming an additive relationship; then fit the regression again assuming an interaction relationship between height and gender. Match the assumptions/interpretations with the appropriate model.

[Hint: make sure you code variable gender appropriately to model the gender effect as instructed.]

  1. The effect of height on weight is the same for male and for female.

  2. The gender difference in weight is the same for any height.

  3. The effect of height on weight is more pronounced among males than among females, i.e. greater positive slope among males.

  4. The gender difference in weight is wider among taller people.

Answer:

Here is the code for creating addition and interactive regression models with summaries.

lm_add <- lm(Weight ~ Height + Gender, data = toy3)
summary(lm_add)

## Call:

Assumption 1: The effect of height on weight is the same for male and for female.

This is suitable for an Addition Model because the slopes of Female’s and Male’s relationship of \(Height\) and \(Weight\) will be the same. This also means that the curves of Female and Male are parallel.

We can create a plot to examine whether an addtion regression model is suitable for this assumption.

# Summarize coefficients from the addition regression model: Intercept for
# Female
lm_add_int_F <- summary(lm_add)$coef[1]

# Intercept for Male
lm_add_int_M <- summary(lm_add)$coef[1] + summary(lm_add)$coef[3]

# Slope
lm_add_slope <- summary(lm_add)$coef[2]

# Create plot to show the relationship of addition between Female and Male.
ggplot(toy3, aes(x = Height, y = Weight, col = Gender)) + geom_point(alpha = 0.4, 
    shape = 16, size = 2) + scale_color_manual(values = c("#d7191c", "#2c7bb6")) + 
    geom_abline(aes(intercept = lm_add_int_F, slope = lm_add_slope), col = "#d7191c") + 
    geom_abline(aes(intercept = lm_add_int_M, slope = lm_add_slope), col = "#2c7bb6")

Assumption 2: The gender difference in weight is the same for any height.

This is suitable for an Addition Model because the slope of Female’s and Male’s relationships of \(Weight\) and \(Height\) will be the same. This also means that the curves of Female and Male are parallel.

We can create a plot to examine whether an addtion regression model is suitable for this assumption.

# Create a new regression model and summarize coefficients.
lm_add2 <- lm(Height ~ Weight + Gender, data = toy3)

# Intercept for Female
lm_add2_int_F <- summary(lm_add2)$coef[1]

# Intercept for Male
lm_add2_int_M <- summary(lm_add2)$coef[1] + summary(lm_add2)$coef[3]

# Slope
lm_add2_slope <- summary(lm_add2)$coef[2]

# Create plot to show the relationship of addition between Female and Male.
ggplot(toy3, aes(x = Weight, y = Height, col = Gender)) + geom_point(alpha = 0.4, 
    shape = 16, size = 2) + scale_color_manual(values = c("#d7191c", "#2c7bb6")) + 
    geom_abline(aes(intercept = lm_add2_int_F, slope = lm_add2_slope), col = "#d7191c") + 
    geom_abline(aes(intercept = lm_add2_int_M, slope = lm_add2_slope), col = "#2c7bb6")

Assumption 3: The effect of height on weight is more pronounced among males than among females, i.e. greater positive slope among males.

This is suitable for an Interactive Model because the slope of Male’s relationship of \(Height\) and \(Weight\) will be greater than the slope of Female’s. This also means that the curves of Female and Male are non-parallel.

We can create a plot to examine whether an interactive regression model is suitable for this assumption.

# Summarize coefficients from the interactive regression model: Intercept
# for Female
lm_inter_int_F <- summary(lm_inter)$coef[1]

# Intercept for Male
lm_inter_int_M <- summary(lm_inter)$coef[1] + summary(lm_inter)$coef[3]

# Slope for Female
lm_inter_slope_F <- summary(lm_inter)$coef[2]

# Slope for Male
lm_inter_slope_M <- summary(lm_inter)$coef[2] + summary(lm_inter)$coef[4]

# Create plot to show the relationship of addition between Female and Male.
ggplot(toy3, aes(x = Height, y = Weight, col = Gender)) + geom_point(alpha = 0.4, 
    shape = 16, size = 2) + scale_color_manual(values = c("#e66101", "#5e3c99")) + 
    geom_abline(aes(intercept = lm_inter_int_F, slope = lm_inter_slope_F), col = "#ca0020") + 
    geom_abline(aes(intercept = lm_inter_int_M, slope = lm_inter_slope_M), col = "#5e3c99")

Assumption 4: The gender difference in weight is wider among taller people.

This is suitable for an Interactive Model because the slope of Male’s relationship of \(Weight\) and \(Height\) will be greater than the slope of Female’s. This also means that the curves of Female and Male are non-parallel.

We can create a plot to examine whether an interactive regression model is suitable for this assumption.

# Create a new regression model and summarize coefficients.
lm_inter2 <- lm(Height ~ Weight * Gender, data = toy3)

# Intercept for Female
lm_inter2_int_F <- summary(lm_inter2)$coef[1]

# Intercept for Male
lm_inter2_int_M <- summary(lm_inter2)$coef[1] + summary(lm_inter2)$coef[3]

# Slope for Female
lm_inter2_slope_F <- summary(lm_inter2)$coef[2]

# Slope for Male
lm_inter2_slope_M <- summary(lm_inter2)$coef[2] + summary(lm_inter2)$coef[4]

# Create plot to show the relationship of addition between Female and Male.
ggplot(toy3, aes(x = Weight, y = Height, col = Gender)) + geom_point(alpha = 0.4, 
    shape = 16, size = 2) + scale_color_manual(values = c("#e66101", "#5e3c99")) + 
    geom_abline(aes(intercept = lm_inter2_int_F, slope = lm_inter2_slope_F), 
        col = "#ca0020") + geom_abline(aes(intercept = lm_inter2_int_M, slope = lm_inter2_slope_M), 
    col = "#5e3c99")

Question 9 of 13

Run two separate regression models, weight on centered height, one for male and one for female (in other words, create two separate datasets, one with just the females and the other with just the males, then run the regression model Weight~height0 for each dataset separately). This approach is also called to stratify the sample based on gender. Examine the results of these two gender specific models, and compare the results with the model you ran in previous questions (\(Weight~height0+gender+height0*gender\)). Choose all the answers that are correct.

[R hint] lm(weight~height0, data=data[data$Gender=="M", ]) lm(weight~height0, data=data[data$Gender=="F", ])

[stata hint] reg weight height0 if Gender=="Male" reg weight height0 if Gender=="Female".

A. The intercept and slope of the male regression line between weight and height(centered) are the same between two approaches.

B. The intercept and slope of the female regression line between weight and height(centered) are the same between two approaches.

C. Whenever comparable, the SEs are greater in the interaction model than in the stratified model(s).

D. The model sum of squares of the interaction model equals to the model sum of squares of the female model plus the model sum of squares of the male model.

E. The model degrees of freedom of the interaction model equals to the model degrees of freedom of male model plus the female model.

F. The residual degrees of freedom of the interaction model equals to the residual degrees of freedom of male model plus the female model.

G. One difference between the two approaches is that in the interaction model we only estimate one model variance, while in the gender stratified approach, we estimate two model variances.

H. One difference between the two approaches is that we now have smaller number of observations in each of the two gender specific models than in the one combined model.

Answer:
toy3_m <- subset(toy3, toy3$Gender == "M")
toy3_f <- subset(toy3, toy3$Gender == "F")

lm_m <- lm(Weight ~ height0, data = toy3_m)
lm_f <- lm(Weight ~ height0, data = toy3_f)

Let’s examine all these assumptions.

A. The intercept and slope of the male regression line between weight and height(centered) are the same between two approaches.

This is TRUE because:

# Intercept and slope of male regression line in lm_m.
lm_m_int <- summary(lm_m)$coef[1]
lm_m_slope <- summary(lm_m)$coef[2]

round(lm_m_int, digits = 4) == round(lm_inter_height0_int_M, digits = 4)
## [1] TRUE
round(lm_m_slope, digits = 4) == round(lm_inter_height0_slope_M, digits = 4)
## [1] TRUE

B. The intercept and slope of the female regression line between weight and height(centered) are the same between two approaches.

This is TRUE because:

# Intercept and slope of female regression line in lm_m.
lm_f_int <- summary(lm_f)$coef[1]
lm_f_slope <- summary(lm_f)$coef[2]

round(lm_f_int, digits = 4) == round(lm_inter_height0_int_F, digits = 4)
## [1] TRUE
round(lm_f_slope, digits = 4) == round(lm_inter_height0_slope_F, digits = 4)
## [1] TRUE

C. Whenever comparable, the SEs are greater in the interaction model than in the stratified model(s).

This is FALSE because:

# The standard error of height0 in the interaction model is not greater than
# the standard error of height0 in the stratified model `lm_m`.
round(summary(lm_inter_height0)$coef[2, 2], digits = 4) > 
round(summary(lm_m)$coef[2, 2], digits = 4)
## [1] FALSE

D. The model sum of squares of the interaction model equals to the model sum of squares of the female model plus the model sum of squares of the male model.

This is FALSE because:

# MSS = TSS - RSS

# The model sum of squares of the interaction model.
lm_inter_height0_TSS <- sum((toy3$Weight - mean(toy3$Weight))^2)
lm_inter_height0_RSS <- sum(lm_inter_height0$resid^2)
lm_inter_height0_MSS <- lm_inter_height0_TSS - lm_inter_height0_RSS

# The model sum of squares of the male model.
lm_m_TSS <- sum((toy3_m$Weight - mean(toy3_m$Weight))^2)
lm_m_RSS <- sum(lm_m$resid^2)
lm_m_MSS <- lm_m_TSS - lm_m_RSS

# The model sum of squares of the female model.
lm_f_TSS <- sum((toy3_f$Weight - mean(toy3_f$Weight))^2)
lm_f_RSS <- sum(lm_f$resid^2)
lm_f_MSS <- lm_f_TSS - lm_f_RSS

# The model sum of squares of the sum of female and male model.
lm_sum_MSS <- lm_m_MSS + lm_f_MSS

paste("The model sum of squares of the interaction model is: ", lm_inter_height0_MSS)
## [1] "The model sum of squares of the interaction model is:  48524.0249527206"
paste("The model sum of squares of the sum of female model and male model is: ", 
    lm_sum_MSS)
## [1] "The model sum of squares of the sum of female model and male model is:  18073.8067596332"
paste("Are they equal? ", lm_inter_height0_MSS == lm_m_MSS + lm_f_MSS, "!")
## [1] "Are they equal?  FALSE !"

E. The model degrees of freedom of the interaction model equals to the model degrees of freedom of male model plus the female model.

This is FALSE because:

# The total model degrees of freedom of the interaction model.
lm_inter_height0_Df <- sum(anova(lm_inter_height0)$Df[1:3])

# The total model degrees of freedom of the male model plus the female
# model.
lm_sum_Df <- anova(lm_m)$Df[1] + anova(lm_f)$Df[1]

paste("The total model degrees of freedom of the interaction model is: ", lm_inter_height0_Df)
## [1] "The total model degrees of freedom of the interaction model is:  3"
paste("The total model degrees of freedom of the male model plus the female model is: ", 
    lm_sum_Df)
## [1] "The total model degrees of freedom of the male model plus the female model is:  2"
paste("Are they equal? ", lm_inter_height0_Df == lm_sum_Df, "!")
## [1] "Are they equal?  FALSE !"

F. The residual degrees of freedom of the interaction model equals to the residual degrees of freedom of male model plus the female model.

This is TRUE because:

# The residual degrees of freedom of the interaction model.
lm_inter_height0_ResiDf <- sum(anova(lm_inter_height0)$Df[4])

# The residual degrees of freedom of the male model plus the female model.
lm_sum_ResiDf <- anova(lm_m)$Df[2] + anova(lm_f)$Df[2]

paste("The residual degrees of freedom of the interaction model is: ", lm_inter_height0_ResiDf)
## [1] "The residual degrees of freedom of the interaction model is:  496"
paste("The residual degrees of freedom of the male model plus the female model is: ", 
    lm_sum_ResiDf)
## [1] "The residual degrees of freedom of the male model plus the female model is:  496"
paste("Are they equal? ", lm_inter_height0_ResiDf == lm_sum_ResiDf, "!")
## [1] "Are they equal?  TRUE !"

G. One difference between the two approaches is that in the interaction model we only estimate one model variance, while in the gender stratified approach, we estimate two model variances.

This is TRUE because:

The interaction model has one variance while there are two model variances in the stratified approach.

Here we plot the interaction model, along with the female model and the male model.

plot_inter <- ggplot(toy3, aes(x = height0, y = Weight, col = Gender)) + scale_color_manual(values = c("#e66101", 
    "#5e3c99")) + theme(legend.position = "none") + geom_jitter(position = position_jitter(width = 0.05), 
    alpha = 0.5)
plot_f <- ggplot(toy3_f, aes(x = height0, y = Weight)) + geom_jitter(color = "#e66101", 
    position = position_jitter(width = 0.05), alpha = 0.5)
plot_m <- ggplot(toy3_m, aes(x = height0, y = Weight)) + geom_jitter(color = "#5e3c99", 
    position = position_jitter(width = 0.05), alpha = 0.5)

plot1 <- plot_inter
plot2 <- plot_f
plot3 <- plot_m
grid.arrange(plot_inter, plot_f, plot_m, nrow = 3)

H. One difference between the two approaches is that we now have smaller number of observations in each of the two gender specific models than in the one combined model.

This is TRUE because:

# Number of observations in the interaction model.
n_inter <- dim(toy3)[1]

# Number of observations in the female model.
n_f <- dim(toy3_f)[1]

# Number of observations in the male model.
n_m <- dim(toy3_m)[1]

n_inter > n_f
## [1] TRUE
n_inter > n_m
## [1] TRUE

In the following questions, you will reanalyze the class example of birthweight and race using toy_ex3.csv.

Question 10 of 13

Fit a regression of birth weight on race using Hispanic as reference group, and match the regression coefficients below.

Hint: You can either generate dummy variables to represent the race variable (code below) or re-level the Race variable so that the reference group is Hispanic:

dat$White <- as.numeric(dat$Race=="W")`

dat$Black <- as.numeric(dat$Race=="B")

dat$Hispanic <- as.numeric(dat$Race=="H")

dat$Other <- as.numeric(dat$Race=="O")

Answer:
# Import the data
dat <- read.csv("toy_ex3.csv", header = TRUE)

dat$White <- as.numeric(dat$Race == "W")
dat$Black <- as.numeric(dat$Race == "B")
dat$Hispanic <- as.numeric(dat$Race == "H")
dat$Other <- as.numeric(dat$Race == "O")

lm_race <- lm(BirthWeight ~ White + Black + Other, data = dat)
coef_white <- summary(lm_race)$coef[2]
coef_black <- summary(lm_race)$coef[3]
coef_other <- summary(lm_race)$coef[4]

Black: -42.3

White: 120.3

Other: 154.8

round(abs(coef_black), digits = 2)
